<subSubSection id="7B1D61BF045731EDB4E0A8C1B97290C5" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="F4E978CEB2FECDF1EF950525B14E2C28" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6E6646906B01AB2A4DCD87E1C5F6EB0D" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
<taxonomicName id="69F658B8F3A0757891FA9EED3E6B183A" authority="Moreira &amp; Vargas, 2018" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Vargas" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Andescecidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andescecidium" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andescecidium</taxonomicName>
gen. n. resembles 
<taxonomicName id="8B9F5E9E131A72C7EACE4519ECB32A97" authority="Moreira &amp; Gonçalves, 2017" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Gonçalves" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Cecidonius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cecidonius" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cecidonius</taxonomicName>
in having pupae bearing strong spines on the anterior margins of the abdominal terga and larvae with two stemmata, which make them unique among cecidosids. However, 
<taxonomicName id="8F7B1494DACADB6D81779C1F9E9B2FFE" authority="Moreira &amp; Vargas, 2018" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Vargas" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Andescecidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andescecidium" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andescecidium</taxonomicName>
shows several adult, larval, and gall features which in conjunction differentiate it from the latter. Adults are much larger, bear mandibular rudiments and have reduced three-segmented maxillary palpi, which are respectively absent and with two in the small 
<taxonomicName id="061DBC8256FA15AB6D237B89625AE865" authority="Moreira &amp; Gonçalves, 2017" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Gonçalves" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Cecidonius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cecidonius" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cecidonius</taxonomicName>
. The ovipositor in 
<taxonomicName id="B997A779DB8912E6C1871D85A8CB5DAB" authority="Moreira &amp; Vargas, 2018" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Vargas" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Andescecidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andescecidium" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andescecidium</taxonomicName>
is reduced in size, and associated with an inconspicuous dorsal crest in the oviscapt cone that is used to lay eggs on superficial external buds. The ovipositor of 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF9E040188AB1A84A27F76954B7B48" authority="Moreira &amp; Gonçalves, 2017" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Gonçalves" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Cecidonius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cecidonius" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cecidonius</taxonomicName>
is very long, having the oviscapt cone dorsally anchored by a conspicuous crest, thus allowing oviposition deep into the stem. Contrary to the larvae of 
<taxonomicName id="B4EAD9791DDE994CAD7E7389E69D6702" authority="Moreira &amp; Gonçalves, 2017" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Gonçalves" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Cecidonius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cecidonius" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cecidonius</taxonomicName>
, which are unique among cecidosids in having setae of much longer size on the thorax, those of 
<taxonomicName id="40F70E4EB0EA98F9ABF4E347F8CD1A9D" authority="Moreira &amp; Vargas, 2018" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Vargas" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Andescecidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andescecidium" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andescecidium</taxonomicName>
show these structures uniform on thorax and abdomen. The spherical galls of 
<taxonomicName id="AE4A07684F23248BF96DC3216012BE90" authority="Moreira &amp; Vargas, 2018" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Vargas" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Andescecidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andescecidium" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andescecidium</taxonomicName>
are associated with stem buds, growing on the external surface from the beginning; they are pedunculate and have fully developed walls. Those of 
<taxonomicName id="CB11526E82BE54CC32A4370C9CAC45B1" authority="Moreira &amp; Gonçalves, 2017" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Gonçalves" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Cecidonius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cecidonius" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cecidonius</taxonomicName>
grow initially under the bark, erupting through the stem surface later in ontogeny, and with their bases remaining open when mature, clogged with feces.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F3047D1A264C61543A65680967CDC9EF" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" type="description">
<paragraph id="8D7950BCA37EF03E712AE32E1DBFF8AC" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Description of adults</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4CEB638EB85E4200E5578ABD197529FD" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
(Figs 2A, B, 3). The adult male morphology was accurately described and illustrated in part by 
<bibRefCitation id="DBE0F299918EFD267292FDDBAE2EA8A0" author="Parra, LE" journalOrPublisher="Nota lepidopterologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" pagination="206 - 214" title="A redescription of Cecidosesargentinana (Cecidosidae) and its early stages, with comments on its taxonomic position." volume="21" year="1998">Parra (1998)</bibRefCitation>
. We complement this description for the male here, adding illustrations that were not provided by Parra, and we also describe the female for the first time.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F11B0FA32827F15DAEB49704A7556806" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
Male. Forewing length ca. 12.1 mm (n = 1). Head (Figure 3A): vertex and frons covered by narrow, elongated dark brown scales with a few scattered whitish gray scales. Compound eyes black. Antennae filiform (~ 0.7
<normalizedToken id="A1D0E4EED6C4901440C736CEEAA1E672" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of forewing), with dark brown scales on scape, pedicel and dorsal surface of basal half of flagellum; filiform sensilla on remaining dorsal and ventral surface of flagellum. Labrum semicircular, short. Mandibles poorly developed, as small stubs. Pilifers absent. Maxillae with galeae reduced to small lobes (~2/3 labial palpus length); maxillary palpi tri-segmented (ratios of segments from base ~1.0:0.8:0.8). Labial palpi tri-segmented (ratios of segments from base ~1.0:0.9:1.2). Maxillary and labial palpi with brownish gray scales. Thorax. Mostly with brownish gray scales. Anterior arms of latero cervical sclerites not observed. Metafurca (Figure 3B) with slender, elongate postero-dorsal apophyses, free from secondary arms. Forewings (Figure 2A, B) lanceolate, mostly covered with brownish gray scales; a broad dark brown spot close to the middle of the posterior margin of discal cell; a small dark brown spot at apex of discal cell. Hindwings lanceolate, brownish gray. Wing venation as described by 
<bibRefCitation id="F291EB19A7B30D5592EF347DA5CF9ED2" author="Parra, LE" journalOrPublisher="Nota lepidopterologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" pagination="206 - 214" title="A redescription of Cecidosesargentinana (Cecidosidae) and its early stages, with comments on its taxonomic position." volume="21" year="1998">Parra (1998</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 2). Prothoracic legs (Figure 3C) dark brown with a few scattered whitish gray scales, bearing an epiphysis on distal portion of tibia. Mesothoracic legs similar in coloration to prothoracic legs, with two whitish gray tibial spurs. Metathoracic legs whitish gray with two pairs of tibial spurs; tibia with longitudinal stripe of narrow, elongated hair-like whitish gray scales. Tibial length proportion (anterior / medium / posterior legs) ~ 0.6:0.7:1.0. Abdomen brownish gray with a few dark brown and scattered whitish gray scales. Male genitalia as described by 
<bibRefCitation id="78FCA93B9B1DD023F614307CBCB64963" author="Parra, LE" journalOrPublisher="Nota lepidopterologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" pagination="206 - 214" title="A redescription of Cecidosesargentinana (Cecidosidae) and its early stages, with comments on its taxonomic position." volume="21" year="1998">Parra (1998</bibRefCitation>
: figs 2, 3, 4A).
</paragraph>
<caption id="251B1B9061731F2F68FE0220EE779D60" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
<paragraph id="7789F796AB9CA99F462740206B54B747" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
Figure 2. Pinned-dried males (holotypes, left) and females (paratypes, right) of 
<taxonomicName id="9C4463BD03E942490556FE4EB2440B00" authority="Moreira &amp; Vargas, 2018" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Vargas" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Andescecidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andescecidium parrai" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parrai">Andescecidium parrai</taxonomicName>
(A, B) and 
<taxonomicName id="367CEB491DF01096EA4730F12FD21BF0" authority="Brèthes, 1916" authorityName="Brèthes" authorityYear="1916" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Oliera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oliera saizi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saizi">Oliera saizi</taxonomicName>
(C, D), dorsal view. Scale bars: 2 mm (A, B), 1 mm (C, D).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="106649F8A841B4A5626CC8AB3ED37B3C" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
Female. Forewing length ca. 11.5 mm (n = 2). Similar to male in general, except that sensilla are less abundant and smaller on the antennae, and abdominal sternum VII with caudal margin more sclerotized, bearing a dense ring of stout, elongate setae (Figure 3E). Female genitalia formed by an oviscapt cone (sensu 
<bibRefCitation id="7F9A791086FF1C86069F76D66C7E864C" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Kristensen 2003</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="491BEDE6BE0FF57F15290515C642B5BE" author="San Blas, G" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" pagination="371 - 384" title="Redescription of Dicranosescapsulifex Kieffer and Joergensen (Lepidoptera: Cecidosidae) with description of the immature stages and biology." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3682.2.9" volume="3682" year="2013">San Blas and Davis 2013</bibRefCitation>
), with weak internal dorsal crest, reaching the anterior margin of tergum seven. Anterior apophyses extending to anterior margin of sixth abdominal segment. Posterior apophyses ~1.3
<normalizedToken id="2843ECB81DE7CF6B3783C6DAB1FF8D9E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of anterior apophyses. Posterior apophyses are caudally fused to form the short, compressed, and sagittate apex of the ovipositor. Ductus and corpus bursae membranous, the latter saculiform, without signum.
</paragraph>
<caption id="2CE47FEC6044CD214E7D12EBD14DB2BA" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
<paragraph id="BDA1BDD66197CA7BD5239FD469F54577" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
Figure 3. 
<taxonomicName id="4640A1814D8131B450F50133A0E7F8F3" authority="Moreira &amp; Vargas, 2018" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Vargas" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Andescecidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andescecidium parrai" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parrai">Andescecidium parrai</taxonomicName>
adult morphology under light microscopy (LMCI 218-03). A head, anterior view B metathoracic furcasternum, posterior (closed arrow points to left furcal apophysis) C fore-, median- and hindlegs, from left to right, respectively D female genitalia, dorsal (open and closed arrows point to the anterior ends of left anterior and posterior right apophyses, respectively) E distal portion of female genitalia in detail, lateral (enlarged area marked by rectangle in D; closed arrow points to the ovipositor tip; asterisk identifies oviscapt seen by transparency; bracket indicates distal margin of sternum eight). Scale bars: 0.3 mm (A, B), 1 mm (C), 0.2 mm (D, E).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FB064229870E5B0252356F8A3362CACC" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="5FC0B1AF3B4860ABD18F83B6A0BE4F08" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="80029E709789C01950F00FAFB6014B17" pageId="0" pageNumber="127">
The genus name is derived from a composition between the Portuguese 
<taxonomicName id="1EC49BD53A0BFAD92A51A8F58ED08847" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Andes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andes" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andes</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="03A15D71C17FE4792B7098952017427B" genus="Cecidia" lsidName="Cecidia" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" rank="genus">Cecidia</taxonomicName>
(a gall; from the Greek 
<normalizedToken id="2DA7FFCBA447C260B2F4B204BA7D9A1E" originalValue="kekídion">kekidion</normalizedToken>
). Thus, the epithet refers to the 
<taxonomicName id="3A2C6BDA45A100C705D50BFFD5A9FD38" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Andes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andes" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andes</taxonomicName>
Mountains where the galls of 
<taxonomicName id="8BE4199D7CECE0F1249C22CE7FA8B247" authority="Moreira &amp; Vargas, 2018" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Vargas" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Cecidosidae" genus="Andescecidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andescecidium" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andescecidium</taxonomicName>
were first found.
</paragraph>
